---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
import TimingHistogram from "../components/charts/TimingHistogram";
import EngagementScatter from "../components/charts/EngagementScatter";
import VideoVsSocialChart from "../components/charts/VideoVsSocialChart";
---

<Layout title="Report">
  <article class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-6 py-16">
    <header class="mb-16 animate-in">
      <h1 class="text-4xl font-extrabold tracking-tight mb-4 leading-tight">What Separates Winners from Everyone Else?</h1>
      <p class="text-muted-foreground text-lg">A data analysis of 4,219 real posts across three Figma × Contra Makeathon editions. June 2026.</p>
    </header>

    <section class="mb-16 animate-in animate-in-delay-1">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-4 text-foreground">The Core Pattern</h2>
      <p class="text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed mb-4">
        After scraping <strong class="text-foreground font-semibold">6,030 posts</strong> from Contra's API
        and filtering to 4,219 in-window submissions across three editions, one signal dominates:
        winners generate significantly more engagement than the crowd. Across all editions,
        winning posts averaged <strong class="text-foreground font-semibold">54.4 likes</strong> versus <strong class="text-foreground font-semibold">7.1</strong> for non-winners, a <strong class="text-foreground font-semibold">7.7× gap</strong>.
      </p>
      <ul class="space-y-2 text-muted-foreground ml-4">
        <li>Engagement gap: <strong class="text-foreground font-semibold">7.7×</strong> more likes for winners (54.4 vs 7.1 avg)</li>
        <li>Video presence: <strong class="text-foreground font-semibold">40–90% of winners</strong> included video vs 7–56% of non-winners</li>
        <li>Early posting edge: winners posted at avg <strong class="text-foreground font-semibold">day 5.4</strong> in Sep 2025 (non-winners: day 6.2)</li>
        <li>Lee Black won across two consecutive editions with entirely different projects</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-16">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-6 text-foreground animate-in">Edition-by-Edition Breakdown</h2>

      <div class="mb-10 animate-in animate-in-delay-1">
        <h3 class="font-semibold mb-3">Figma Make-a-thon (Sep 3–10, 2025)</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground mb-3">
          $100K prize pool. 1,773 in-window posts scraped (from 2,933 total on <code>figmamakeathon2025</code> tag).
          Cara Ellis's winning Web Poetry post ranked 3rd by likes in the entire window with 217 likes on day 6.
        </p>
        <div class="overflow-x-auto rounded-xl border border-border">
          <table>
            <thead><tr><th>Metric</th><th class="text-right">Winners (5)</th><th class="text-right">Non-Winners (1,768)</th></tr></thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr><td class="font-medium">Avg Likes</td><td class="text-right font-semibold">69</td><td class="text-right">4.1</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="font-medium">Engagement Multiplier</td><td class="text-right font-semibold">16.8×</td><td class="text-right">—</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="font-medium">Avg Post Day</td><td class="text-right">Day 5.4</td><td class="text-right">Day 6.2</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="font-medium">Has Video</td><td class="text-right">40%</td><td class="text-right">7.5%</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="font-medium">Top Post</td><td class="text-right">Cara Ellis: Web Poetry (217 lk)</td><td class="text-right">Anushriya Bhardwaj (222 lk)</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
        <p class="text-xs text-muted-foreground mt-2">
          Cara Ellis's 217-like Web Poetry post was one of the top 3 most-liked posts during the entire 8-day window.
          The non-winner top post (222 lk) was also a high-quality interaction design entry.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="mb-10 animate-in animate-in-delay-2">
        <h3 class="font-semibold mb-3">Figma Makeathon March 2026 (Feb 1 – Mar 16)</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground mb-3">
          $100K prize pool. Six categories. 1,497 in-window posts from 1,508 scraped.
        </p>
        <div class="overflow-x-auto rounded-xl border border-border">
          <table>
            <thead><tr><th>Metric</th><th class="text-right">Winners (10)</th><th class="text-right">Non-Winners (1,487)</th></tr></thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr><td class="font-medium">Avg Likes</td><td class="text-right font-semibold">55.4</td><td class="text-right">9.3</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="font-medium">Engagement Multiplier</td><td class="text-right font-semibold">6.0×</td><td class="text-right">—</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="font-medium">Avg Post Day</td><td class="text-right">Day 30.3</td><td class="text-right">Day 30.3</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="font-medium">Has Video</td><td class="text-right">90%</td><td class="text-right">56.2%</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="font-medium">Top Winner Posts</td><td class="text-right" colspan="2">Lee Black / Airwwave (222 lk), Charlota Blunárová / Common Thread (173 lk)</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
        <p class="text-xs text-muted-foreground mt-2">
          Video presence is the strongest signal: 90% of winners included a video vs 56% of non-winners.
          Timing showed no advantage — winners and non-winners posted at the same average day in the 44-day window.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="mb-10 animate-in animate-in-delay-3">
        <h3 class="font-semibold mb-3">Config Makeathon 2026 (Jun 4–18)</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground mb-3">
          $100K prize pool. Six categories including "Build In Public." 949 in-window posts from 1,589 scraped.
        </p>
        <div class="overflow-x-auto rounded-xl border border-border">
          <table>
            <thead><tr><th>Metric</th><th class="text-right">Winners (12)</th><th class="text-right">Non-Winners (937)</th></tr></thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr><td class="font-medium">Avg Likes</td><td class="text-right font-semibold">47.5</td><td class="text-right">9.3</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="font-medium">Engagement Multiplier</td><td class="text-right font-semibold">5.1×</td><td class="text-right">—</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="font-medium">Avg Post Day</td><td class="text-right">Day 10.2</td><td class="text-right">Day 10.7</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="font-medium">Has Video</td><td class="text-right">67%</td><td class="text-right">59%</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="font-medium">Grand Prize Winner</td><td class="text-right">Bene Brandhofer / Visual Atlas</td><td class="text-right">Top non-winner: Falcon Studio (380 lk)</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
        <p class="text-xs text-muted-foreground mt-2">
          The engagement gap narrows here: the #1 most-liked post (Falcon Studio, 380 likes) did not win.
          The grand prize went to Visual Atlas despite lower engagement — quality of interaction design outweighed raw popularity.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-16">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-4 text-foreground animate-in">The Timing Effect</h2>
      <p class="text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed mb-4 animate-in animate-in-delay-1">
        In the 8-day Sep 2025 window, winners posted at avg <strong class="text-foreground font-semibold">day 5.4</strong>
        vs <strong class="text-foreground font-semibold">day 6.2</strong> for non-winners — a small but real edge.
        In March 2026's 44-day window, timing was identical. In Config 2026's 15-day window, almost no difference.
        Early posting helps in short-window contests; in longer ones, quality of work matters more.
      </p>
      <div class="rounded-xl border border-border p-6 bg-card animate-in animate-in-delay-2">
        <TimingHistogram client:load />
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-16">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-4 text-foreground animate-in">The Engagement Signal</h2>
      <p class="text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed mb-4 animate-in animate-in-delay-1">
        Across 4,219 in-window posts, winners averaged <strong class="text-foreground font-semibold">7.7× more likes</strong>
        than non-winners. This isn't circular — engagement reflects genuine community interest that
        judges also respond to. Cara Ellis's Web Poetry ranked 3rd by likes in the Sep 2025 window.
        Lee Black's Airwwave ranked 2nd in March 2026. High engagement and winning co-occur
        because both stem from the same thing: making something people actually want to share.
      </p>
      <div class="rounded-xl border border-border p-6 bg-card animate-in animate-in-delay-2">
        <EngagementScatter client:load />
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-16">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-4 text-foreground animate-in">The Video Effect</h2>
      <p class="text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed mb-4 animate-in animate-in-delay-1">
        Video presence is the most consistent signal across all editions.
        In March 2026: <strong class="text-foreground font-semibold">90% of winners</strong> had video vs 56% of non-winners.
        In Config 2026: 67% vs 59%. In Sep 2025: 40% vs 7.5%.
        A working video demo shows the interaction is real, reduces skepticism, and drives shares.
      </p>
      <div class="rounded-xl border border-border p-6 bg-card animate-in animate-in-delay-2">
        <VideoVsSocialChart client:load />
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-16 animate-in">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-4 text-foreground">What This Means for Participants</h2>
      <ol class="space-y-3 text-muted-foreground ml-4 list-decimal">
        <li><strong class="text-foreground font-semibold">Include a video demo</strong> — the single strongest predictor across all three editions (40–90% of winners vs 7–56% of non-winners)</li>
        <li><strong class="text-foreground font-semibold">Build something genuinely shareable</strong> — the 7.7× engagement gap is real; high likes and winning co-occur because quality drives both</li>
        <li><strong class="text-foreground font-semibold">Post early in short windows</strong> — in the 8-day Sep 2025 contest, winners posted 0.8 days earlier on average; time for engagement to compound matters</li>
        <li><strong class="text-foreground font-semibold">Understand the categories before you start</strong> — Config 2026 added "Build In Public" and "Innovative Workflow"; winning strategies changed accordingly</li>
        <li><strong class="text-foreground font-semibold">Engagement isn't everything in Config-style contests</strong> — Falcon Studio had 380 likes and didn't place; the grand prize went to quality of interaction design</li>
        <li><strong class="text-foreground font-semibold">Come back for the next one</strong> — Lee Black is the only two-time winner across all three editions (Airwwave in March, Connected Earth in Config)</li>
      </ol>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-8 rounded-2xl border border-border p-6 bg-card animate-in">
      <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-3">Methodology</h2>
      <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed mb-2">
        6,030 posts scraped via authenticated Contra GraphQL API calls from within the browser
        (session cookies enabled access beyond the anonymous 2,020-result API cap).
        Two sort passes per edition (ENGAGEMENT + CREATED_AT) to maximize unique post capture.
        Filtered to in-contest-window posts only: Sep 3–10 2025, Feb 1–Mar 16 2026, Jun 4–18 2026.
        Official announcement posts excluded. Winner detection via project name + creator name matching.
      </p>
      <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground">
        Scraped: <strong class="text-foreground">2,933</strong> Sep 2025 ·
        <strong class="text-foreground">1,508</strong> March 2026 ·
        <strong class="text-foreground">1,589</strong> Config 2026.
        In-window analyzed: <strong class="text-foreground">1,773 + 1,497 + 949 = 4,219 posts</strong>.
      </p>
    </section>
  </article>
</Layout>
